My GF and I went to Gary Danko after two months of waiting! It was incredible. Environment: As you walk in you are greeted with a soft color palette and warm tones that make you feel right at home. The dining rooms are not deathly quiet, but there is an electricity in the air, everyone there is here to experience the best that SF has to offer. Most men wear sports coats or button down shirts, and most women in dresses or nice blouses. Food: I opted for the 4 course dinner without dessert and 3 wine pairings for my seafood, savory, and cheese plates. The food was impeccable, I started with Dungeness crab salad that was sublime. Paired with small slices of grapefruit, the salad was a perfect way to start. The next dish was the lobster and potato purée, which was insanely good as well. The flavors paired very nicely and the wine pairing was spot on. It contrasted the savory tastes of the lobster with some acidity. The third course was a duck dish that was my least favorite of my dishes, however still terrific. The only issue I found was inconsistent flavor on all the slices of duck. The wine pairing with this dish was the best though, the pairing was perfect, as though the sommelier sat with the dish and wines for hours. Lastly we each chose the cheese plates which had a selection of 20 terrific cheeses. The wine pairing with the cheeses was a more broad Madeira to pair with all of the different flavors and it was tasty! Experience: Overall the reason you should go to Gary Danko is because you want to experience the best of the best. From the ambience to the food and everything in between, GD is fantastic. They even hold a napkin when pouring water so you don't get splashed! They truly are masters at their craft at GD, and if you are able to go, GO!

This may have been one of the best dining experiences I've ever had. And I've been to my fair share of high-end restaurants and tried tasting menus across the U.S. and abroad. Not only was the food absolutely sublime, but so was the service. The receptionist was kind and our waiters were THE BEST! The main waiter was super attentive and diligent at explaining everything being served and treating us special. They gave us a small portion of a squash soup before we ordered our food and it was the most delicious bite ever! Even their bread is delicious, which they said they get from La Brea Bakery in Los Angeles. When we were done with our different courses, they gave us a plate of yummy petit-fours. And right before we left, the waiter handed us to-go gifts. To my surprise and delight, they were the most delicious banana bread muffins I've ever tasted (with cream cheese filling). We tried 7 different dishes altogether and they were all super good so I am sure everything on the menu is delicious. I can't wait to come back here for a special occasion. I highly recommend this restaurant!

1. Phone reservations are so courteous and helpful. +1 STAR 2. Valet parking in SF at a high end restaurant is only $12. +0.5 STARS 3. The dining room is divided on opposite sides of the bar, with restrooms for each respective side, creating an intimate dining experience where the restroom is close by and the sound does not get out of control like at some restaurant dining rooms. +0.5 STARS 4. All the staff inside is so nice, so professional, seem to genuinely enjoy their jobs and take pride in what they do. There was a level of polish in service that is sadly absent in other SF fine dining restaurants. +2 STARS 5. The food is phenomenal. Fresh, high quality ingredients, thoughtfully and skillfully prepared, elegantly presented, really just beautiful and exquisite dining complemented by great service. Favorites included the soups and the Moroccan stuffed squab which visually grossed out my vegetarian dining companion but delighted me! He LOVED his vegetarian menu though, and I can see why vegetarians love this place as they have a whole separate (and equally wonderful - NOT an afterthought) menu for them. +4 STARS 6. Bathrooms are spacious with lighted, magnified mirrors for the ladies (and men who care). +0.5 STARS 7. They provide you with a Gary Danko shawl when THEY NOTICE you are cold and send you home with a complimentary packaged Gary Danko dessert. +0.5 STARS So, that totals 9 STARS on a 5 STAR scale. Yeah, I love this place. I also loved the guy whose sole job was to go around refreshing people's bread. Some places act stingy with their bread - not here! I was inhaling their bread so that I could keep enjoying their BUTTER that is SO tasty. And yet I still ate every bit of my 38 course meal, hahaha. They also have a prosecco that is TO DIE FOR, that even non-prosecco-lovers like. There is seriously so much I love about this place!!

I was expecting good food, but I received great food. I have been to many restaurants; there were always hits and misses when it comes to fine dining. Gary Danko was the exception and I was really surprised. When I looked at the menu, it's fairly traditional of what you would expect on an old school "fancy" restaurant. You know, the usuals such as lobster, caviar, oysters, and soufflés. Therefore, I expected it to be good but not as amazing as I experienced it. I have to start with the service. While some may find it stuffy, I found it to be completely professional but easy. They timed everything perfectly. I know that the waiters were keeping an eye on us to provide impeccable service, but you couldn't really feel it. From start to finish, they made the two hour dinner so amazing that time flew bye. The attention to detail was simply astonishing. From bringing our drinks to from the bar to our table all the way to giving us our beautifully packaged leftovers when we were about to exit, the service was simply astounding. They did a wonderful job timing the courses, which was hard because I opted for four courses while my boyfriend opted for their five course tasting menu. Also the staff were extremely knowledgeable but there wasn't an ounce of pretentiousness in their demeanor. My boyfriend and I have a ritual of playing thumb war (I won this round) during every meal. They didn't give us the dirty eye for this. Their service was really welcoming and informative. It made the evening so nice and special. They even brought our a beautiful mousse, gratis, for our anniversary. I think I made really good selections for my courses. I started off with their oyster in a pea sauce, topped with caviar. When I ate the caviar and oyster without much sauce, I was not that enthused. However, once I added a lot of the sauce to my spoon, the flavor combination was simply delicious. I cannot get over how great it was all together. I wanted to lick my bowl to savor every last drop. For the second course, I ordered the lobster on top of corn and potato puree. Once again, the mix of flavors worked so well. I couldn't get enough of the sauce on the potatoes and the lobster was cook beautifully. The lobster was so sweet and delicate, cooked exactly how it should have been. Then, for the third course, I ordered the guinea hen. It's chicken right, but I have never had a bird cooked so wonderfully. Seriously, the hen was so moist and yet the skin was so crispy. At this point of the meal, I was getting extremely full. Next time, I will only do three courses. My boyfriend shared his cheese course with me. I think they curated their cheese selections well, because all the cheese we chose were simply amazing. The raisin bread added such a perfect contrast to the cheese. Finally, for dessert, I was craving a soufflé. It's such an old school dessert but I was craving it. The Village Pub's soufflé didn't completey "wow" me, so I was looking for a better one. This was 1000x better! I couldn't get enough. I wanted to scrape every last piece. As a treat, we were given a mousse cake for our anniversary, as well as, petit sized desserts given to every guest. We had them pack it to go because we couldn't finish it all. After all that, the chef gave us a pineapple breakfast cake. We had it this morning and it was simply delicious. It a clever way to remind you of the dinner before by treating you to breakfast the next morning. I definitely want to go again!

I had to give it 5 stars; plus the little gift at the end definitely made my night.

Gary Danko serves really good food with really good service. At their prices, they'd better. The problem is that there are many restaurants in San Francisco that can do the same or better for less. I value the food much more than the service, so in terms of just the food, without consideration of price, I'd rank Gary Danko, compared to other "nice" restaurants in the Bay Area as follows: 1. Frances 2. Kokkari 3. State Bird Provisions 4. Commis 5. Gary Danko 6. Chapeau So it doesn't rank very high in my book, and to top it off, it's probably the most expensive. The best dishes we had here were the seared scallops (among the best I've had) and the banana flambe dessert. Everything else, while very good, wasn't mind-blowingly good as you might expect from such a highly rated restaurant. I can't complain about the service though. It's probably tied for the top service I've received from anywhere.

Gary Danko is a SF legendary restaurant. While their cuisine has stood the test of time, as well as their impeccable service and consistency in delivering Michelin star gastronomic excellence, the lack of evolution puts it a bit in the early 2000's. Come here for a "must have experience". But no need try it again later, as the menu essentially never changes.

Dined at Gary Danko a few times in the past, but it has been a few years since my last time here. I didn't remember how awesome this place was until we dined here again this passed weekend. You get such a great value for the price and quality of food you get here. The food is consistently good and portions are generous. If you opt for the 5 course meal, my advice is not to be greedy and don't get multiple main course dishes even though you can because you will get really full really fast and that makes it hard to appreciate the rest of the dishes. Some of our favorites include: Dungeness Crab Salad, Risotto with Rock Shrimp & Dungeness Crab, Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Branzini, Juniper Crusted Venison, Cheese Cart and Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces. The service is decent and on par for a one-Michelin starred restaurant. Reservations are hard to make, but not impossible, just make sure you reserve at least a month and a half in advance especially for a weekend.

    7.  They provide you with a Gary Danko shawl when THEY NOTICE you are cold and send you home with a complimentary packaged Gary Danko dessert.  +0.5 STARS

    8/24/2014

    I was expecting good food, but I received great food.

    I have been to many restaurants; there were always hits and misses when it comes to fine dining.

    Gary Danko was the exception and I was really surprised. When I looked at the menu, it's fairly traditional of what you would expect on an old school "fancy" restaurant. You know, the usuals such as lobster, caviar, oysters, and soufflés. Therefore, I expected it to be good but not as amazing as I experienced it.

    I have to start with the service. While some may find it stuffy, I found it to be completely professional but easy. They timed everything perfectly. I know that the waiters were keeping an eye on us to provide impeccable service, but you couldn't really feel it. From start to finish, they made the two hour dinner so amazing that time flew bye. The attention to detail was simply astonishing. From bringing our drinks to from the bar to our table all the way to giving us our beautifully packaged leftovers when we were about to exit, the service was simply astounding.  

    They did a wonderful job timing the courses, which was hard because I opted for four courses while my boyfriend opted for their five course tasting menu. Also the staff were extremely knowledgeable but there wasn't an ounce of pretentiousness in their demeanor. My boyfriend and I have a ritual of playing thumb war (I won this round) during every meal. They didn't give us the dirty eye for this. Their service was really welcoming and informative. It made the evening so nice and special. They even brought our a beautiful mousse, gratis, for our anniversary.

    I think I made really good selections for my courses. I started off with their oyster in a pea sauce, topped with caviar. When I ate the caviar and oyster without much sauce, I was not that enthused. However, once I added a lot of the sauce to my spoon, the flavor combination was simply delicious. I cannot get over how great it was all together. I wanted to lick my bowl to savor every last drop.

    For the second course, I ordered the lobster on top of corn and potato puree. Once again, the mix of flavors worked so well. I couldn't get enough of the sauce on the potatoes and the lobster was cook beautifully. The lobster was so sweet and delicate, cooked exactly how it should have been.

    Then, for the third course, I ordered the guinea hen. It's chicken right, but I have never had a bird cooked so wonderfully. Seriously, the hen was so moist and yet the skin was so crispy. At this point of the meal, I was getting extremely full. Next time, I will only do three courses.

    My boyfriend shared his cheese course with me. I think they curated their cheese selections well, because all the cheese we chose were simply amazing. The raisin bread added such a perfect contrast to the cheese.

    Finally, for dessert, I was craving a soufflé. It's such an old school dessert but I was craving it. The Village Pub's soufflé didn't completey "wow" me, so I was looking for a better one. This was 1000x better! I couldn't get enough. I wanted to scrape every last piece.

    As a treat, we were given a mousse cake for our anniversary, as well as, petit sized desserts given to every guest. We had them pack it to go because we couldn't finish it all. After all that, the chef gave us a pineapple breakfast cake. We had it this morning and it was simply delicious. It a clever way to remind you of the dinner before by treating you to breakfast the next morning. I definitely want to go again!

    12/24/2014

    Gary Danko serves really good food with really good service. At their prices, they'd better. The problem is that there are many restaurants in San Francisco that can do the same or better for less. I value the food much more than the service, so in terms of just the food, without consideration of price, I'd rank Gary Danko, compared to other "nice" restaurants in the Bay Area as follows:

    1. Frances
    2. Kokkari
    3. State Bird Provisions
    4. Commis
    5. Gary Danko
    6. Chapeau

    So it doesn't rank very high in my book, and to top it off, it's probably the most expensive. The best dishes we had here were the seared scallops (among the best I've had) and the banana flambe dessert. Everything else, while very good, wasn't mind-blowingly good as you might expect from such a highly rated restaurant.

    I can't complain about the service though. It's probably tied for the top service I've received from anywhere.

    Been here twice in the last 6 months. I would give GD 5 stars, but the last experience wasn't so great..I will explain.

    The first time I went to GD, service was exceptional, the food was equally exceptional. The plates arrived warm and my party had a wonderful evening! I should mention that we began dinner service at 7pm. I was really happy that the portions of the food were generous, I had expected to get tiny plates, but I left GD pleasantly stuffed! The first time was worth every penny and the experience was unforgettable. I definitely agree with the other reviewer that the decor felt like I was time traveling back into the 90's. However, the restaurant still felt elegant and not stuffy.

    The second time I went to GD, we started dinner at 9pm (since my boyfriend really wanted to try GD and I decided to try to secure reservations about 3 weeks before our trip and this was the only time they had available, this was also the first time the bf was visiting SF, thought I'd add that in there for context). I think that was our mistake. We shouldn't have had dinner so late. The food was was still good, though not exceptional due to the fact that a couple of the plates were COLD. Since I had the same order only a couple of months before, I knew what the food should have tasted like. I was disappointed the second time around since this was the first time my boyfriend was dining here and I had hyped up the place based on my first experience and was pretty sure everything would have been perfect. But alas, it was not.

    If it's your first time coming to GD, I would defnitely try to get there earlier and not dine there late since they are wrapping up service and I'm sure the staff is exhausted by then (our waitstaff was very friendly and attentive still). BUT, it's Gary friggin' Danko. I hold them at a much higher standard. I expected perfection like the last, especially if most diners come here for the experience and for special occasions (not to mention we spent a good $500+ for dinner). It's okay though, I'll still go back. Lol.

    2/27/2017

    Dined at Gary Danko a few times in the past, but it has been a few years since my last time here. I didn't remember how awesome this place was until we dined here again this passed weekend. You get such a great value for the price and quality of food you get here. The food is consistently good and portions are generous. If you opt for the 5 course meal, my advice is not to be greedy and don't get multiple main course dishes even though you can because you will get really full really fast and that makes it hard to appreciate the rest of the dishes.

    Some of our favorites include: Dungeness Crab Salad, Risotto with Rock Shrimp & Dungeness Crab, Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Branzini, Juniper Crusted Venison, Cheese Cart and Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces.

    The service is decent and on par for a one-Michelin starred restaurant. Reservations are hard to make, but not impossible, just make sure you reserve at least a month and a half in advance especially for a weekend.
